WEBVTT

00:00:00.430 --> 00:00:04.000
Now that you are ready to use PyAnalySeries, an important

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:06.770
point is how to work with your data, in other

00:00:06.770 --> 00:00:08.810
words, how to import series.

00:00:09.970 --> 00:00:13.590
Many scientists working with field or instrumental data rely on

00:00:13.590 --> 00:00:14.980
spreadsheet formats.

00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:19.820
For this reason, PyAnalySeries allows you to directly copy and

00:00:19.820 --> 00:00:23.060
paste data from your spreadsheet into the import window.

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:26.280
Let’s look at this in more detail.

00:00:29.380 --> 00:00:32.050
Let’s open a new worksheet to host our data.

00:00:35.230 --> 00:00:37.380
Rename the file if needed.

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:47.040
Data can be imported in X, Y format, or with

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:51.370
multiple series such as X, Y1, Y2, Y3.

00:00:51.370 --> 00:00:55.120
From your spreadsheet, select the columns and press Control C

00:00:57.450 --> 00:01:00.700
Then, in the import window available from the Create menu

00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:03.490
press Control V.

00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:16.300
There is no need to clear the import window; simply

00:01:16.300 --> 00:01:18.320
paste your data directly into it.

00:01:19.730 --> 00:01:22.580
Columns can also be reorganized once pasted.

00:01:22.580 --> 00:01:25.400
If the columns are not ordered as X, Y1, Y2

00:01:25.790 --> 00:01:27.960
you can rearrange them as needed.

00:01:34.140 --> 00:01:36.830
Click and hold the column title, then drag it to

00:01:36.830 --> 00:01:38.520
the desired position.

00:01:43.850 --> 00:01:46.390
It is also possible to import a set of pointers

00:01:46.420 --> 00:01:48.830
in X, Y format.

00:01:58.990 --> 00:02:02.000
Missing Y values can be preserved, allowing you to keep

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:04.660
the data exactly as it was originally produced.

00:02:05.820 --> 00:02:08.320
Let’s now examine the effect of this checkbox on the

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:10.470
imported series.

00:02:20.850 --> 00:02:24.350
Import is independent of the decimal separator, whether comma or

00:02:24.350 --> 00:02:25.110
dot.

00:02:25.110 --> 00:02:27.960
Values are internally standardized using the dot.

00:02:29.180 --> 00:02:33.180
Column titles can include LaTeX-style characters, which will be correctly

00:02:33.180 --> 00:02:34.370
rendered in the plots.

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:38.730
You may also want to reorganize items internally.

00:02:38.730 --> 00:02:40.820
Just drag them to the desired order.

00:02:44.940 --> 00:02:47.390
Do not forget to save your worksheet with your imported

00:02:47.390 --> 00:02:49.510
data with a Ctrl S.
